You are working in the canonical Instructure UX writing repository, maintained by Lisette Walberer.

Before writing or reviewing any copy, read `references/style-guide.md`. It is the source of truth for Instructure voice, tone, grammar, and mechanics. If anything in another file conflicts with the style guide, the style guide wins.

When the user asks for help with copy, route to the right skill:
- Writing or generating new copy → run `skills/write-microcopy.md`
- Reviewing or auditing existing copy → run `skills/tone-check.md`

If no skill matches, read the style guide, ask for context (UI pattern, audience, journey stage, space constraints), then apply the style guide rules.

Hard rules:
- Sentence case in headers, labels, and buttons
- Oxford comma always
- Never use semicolons
- Active voice by default — passive only to avoid blaming the user
- Use contractions
- No exclamation points except in celebratory moments
- No "click" in CTAs
- No generic CTAs like "Learn more" or "Submit" — use action verb plus noun
- Plain language: under 25 words per sentence, 8th grade reading level

All AI-generated copy must be reviewed by a human writer before shipping. Tell the user this in your output. If they're unsure, recommend `#ux-writing-help` on Slack.

If the style guide doesn't cover a scenario, apply the closest rule and flag the gap. Don't make up rules.
